<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n10075b"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n10" href="#n10075b">N10 (VI.B.16)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n10all.htm#n10075b"> 75(b)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> (1) cursus pub<span class="strike"><span class="striketext">b</span></span><font color="green">[hour]</font> / 2) angariae /</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">La poste semble na&icirc;tre comme d&apos;elle-m&ecirc;me sur les belles routes construites par les Romains. Elle s&apos;y montre sous deux formes distinctes et parall&egrave;les: le <mark>cursus publicus</mark>, exclusivement affect&eacute;, sous les empereurs comme sous la R&eacute;publique, aux communications &ldquo;officielles&rdquo;, comme nous disons aujourd&apos;hui, et les <mark>angari&aelig;</mark>, faisant le service des correspondances particuli&egrave;res. <font color="green">[The postal service seems to have emerged by itself on the fine roads built by the Romans. There we see two parallel and distinct forms: the cursus publicus, which under the emperors as well as under the Republic was exclusively charged with official communications, as we would call them today; and the angari&aelig;, which is the service for private correspondence.]</font> <small> Arthur de Rothschild, <a name="ARHD" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#ARHD"><cite title="source">Histoire de la poste</cite></a> (1876) 2</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
